buttons.snippet: Rule of thumb is at least 4,000 years old. Foodie tradition dictates only eating wild oysters in months with the letter “r” – from September to April – to avoid watery shellfish, or worse, a nasty bout of food poisoning.

buttons.subtitle: Shellfish Allergies
buttons.title: Shellfish and fish allergies - Better Health Channel
buttons.snippet: The most common symptom is raised red bumps of skin (hives). Other symptoms include wheezing and trouble breathing, cramps, nausea or vomiting. The best way to manage a shellfish or fish allergy is to avoid all food containing the species to which you are allergic. Food allergies can be life threatening.
